4. State Transitions & Safe Rollbacks

Irreversible Changes: The only system-level persistent change is rpm-ostree kargs --append=amdgpu.noretry=0. This is easily reversible via rpm-ostree kargs --delete=amdgpu.noretry=0.

HA Onboarding Transition: The guide explicitly warns not to edit configuration.yaml until the UI onboarding is complete (EX.3, Step 4). This shows a clear understanding of HA's state machine—creating the file prematurely causes a fatal boot loop.

No Circular Dependencies: The execution order (Network -> Containers -> Keys -> UI Setup -> Integrations) is strictly linear and logically sound.

5. Final Validation Checklist

To confirm the system has successfully reached the intended end state without hidden failures, run the following deterministic checks:

SELinux & GPU Check: Trigger a chat in Open WebUI, then run docker exec ollama ollama ps. The output MUST show 100% GPU. If it shows CPU, the SELinux label:disable flag is missing or amdgpu.noretry=0 failed.

Network Isolation Check: Run curl -s -o /dev/null -w "%{http_code}" http://<server-LAN-IP>:11434. It MUST return 000 (Connection refused). If it returns 200, Ollama is dangerously exposed to the LAN.

MCP File Write Permission: In Open WebUI, ask the AI to "Save the word 'Audit' to a file called audit.txt in my notes". Then run sudo cat /var/srv/nextcloud-data/<user>/files/AI-Notes/audit.txt. It MUST output "Audit".

Proxy Forwarding Check: Disconnect from Wi-Fi (use Cellular) and navigate to https://home.<yourdomain>.duckdns.org. It MUST load Home Assistant cleanly without a 400 Bad Request error (verifying the trusted_proxies configuration).

HA WebSocket Integrity: In Home Assistant, open browser Dev Tools (F12) -> Network -> WS. The WebSocket connection must be persistently Connected. If it drops continuously, NPM WebSockets Support was not enabled.

Rating Score: 9.5 / 10

Verdict: Outstanding. This is an elite-tier technical document. It loses half a point exclusively due to the missing SELinux label:disable flag for Docker CE device mapping, which is a common, localized quirk of Fedora Atomic systems. Otherwise, the logic, command safety, and architectural design are flawless.
